There is a better solution to use the PROXY in Angular to overcome CORS.

1. Add a proxy.config.js file in the root folder. 

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

    const PROXY_CONFIG = [
      {
        context: [
          &quot;/api&quot;
        ],
        target: &quot;http://localhost:8888&quot;,
        secure: false,
        logLevel: &quot;debug&quot;,
        changeOrigin: true
      }
    ];

    module.exports = PROXY_CONFIG;

 2. Add `&quot;proxyConfig&quot;: &quot;proxy.config.js&quot;` in the angular.json file under the serve: So when u run ng serve the poxy will be added to the angular node lite server.
[![enter image description here][3]][3]

 3. In your api call you have to call the api as `http://localhost:4200/api/mydomain/path` so from the browser it will be calling the apis in 4200, so the CORS err cannot come as now its calling the same domain.
In the node lite server it will change the url to `http://localhost:8888/mydomain/path` and call the api as a server to server call. You can see the &#39;api&#39; in the URL will be cut off by the proxy server and change the target as provided in the config.


